<FIXTURE>/vulnerable_full.vue
error[vue/security/no-v-html]: Unsafe `v-html` directive renders untrusted HTML
 --> <FIXTURE>/vulnerable_full.vue:2:8
  |
2 |   <div v-html="userInput">x</div>
  |        ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ here
  |
  = help: Rendering untrusted HTML can execute arbitrary JavaScript. Sanitise the input with DOMPurify (or an equivalent library), or use `v-text` / `{ }` interpolation instead.
error[vue/security/no-inner-html]: `.innerHTML` assignment introduces a DOM XSS sink
  --> <FIXTURE>/vulnerable_full.vue:21:1
   |
21 | el.innerHTML = userInput
   | ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ here
   |
   = help: Setting `.innerHTML` from a dynamic value lets an attacker inject script tags and event handlers. Use `textContent` for plain text, or sanitise the value with DOMPurify before insertion.
error[vue/security/no-document-write]: `document.write` is a known XSS sink
  --> <FIXTURE>/vulnerable_full.vue:22:1
   |
22 | document.write('<h1>x</h1>')
   | ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ here
   |
   = help: `document.write` after page load is almost always an XSS risk. Use `appendChild`, `Element.innerHTML` (with sanitisation), or update via Vue reactivity instead.
error[vue/security/no-eval]: `eval` and `new Function` execute arbitrary code
  --> <FIXTURE>/vulnerable_full.vue:23:1
   |
23 | eval(input)
   | ^^^^^^^^^^^ here
   |
   = help: `eval` (and `new Function`) execute strings as JavaScript. With any attacker-controlled substring this is RCE. Refactor to a static expression, a lookup table, or `Function.prototype` bindings.
error[vue/security/no-open-redirect]: Unvalidated value is forwarded to a navigation sink
  --> <FIXTURE>/vulnerable_full.vue:24:1
   |
24 | location.href = next
   | ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ here
   |
   = help: Forwarding user-controlled data to `location.*` is a classic open-redirect vector. Validate the URL against an allow-list of hostnames before navigating, or use a router-managed navigation helper.
error[vue/security/no-unsafe-localstorage]: Auth-looking value is being written to `localStorage`
  --> <FIXTURE>/vulnerable_full.vue:25:1
   |
25 | localStorage.setItem('auth_token', jwt)
   | ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ here
   |
   = help: Tokens in `localStorage` are reachable by any script running on the page (including injected ones) and persist across sessions. Prefer an `HttpOnly; Secure` cookie set by the server, or use `sessionStorage` for short-lived data.
warning[vue/security/no-unsafe-iframe]: `iframe` is missing a `sandbox` attribute
 --> <FIXTURE>/vulnerable_full.vue:4:3
  |
4 |   <iframe src="https://example.com"></iframe>
  |   ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ here
  |
  = help: An `iframe` without `sandbox` inherits the embedding origin's full capabilities. Add at minimum `sandbox=""` (or an explicit allow-list) to neutralise framed content that turns malicious.
error[vue/security/no-dynamic-bind-src]: Dynamic `src` binding can load untrusted resources
 --> <FIXTURE>/vulnerable_full.vue:5:8
  |
5 |   <img :src="userAvatar">
  |        ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ here
  |
  = help: Validate and sanitise the URL before binding it. Allow only an explicit allow-list of schemes (https, /) and hosts, and never concatenate user input into the URL.
error[vue/security/no-postmessage-wildcard]: `postMessage` is called with a wildcard `targetOrigin` of `'*'`
  --> <FIXTURE>/vulnerable_full.vue:26:1
   |
26 | iframe.contentWindow.postMessage({ type: 'ping' }, '*')
   | ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ here
   |
   = help: Always pin a specific `targetOrigin` (for example `https://app.example.com`). The wildcard `'*'` lets a malicious site that has navigated the target window intercept the message. Use the URL of the receiver, or `/` only when you genuinely want same-origin delivery.
error[vue/security/no-window-open-blank-noopener]: `window.open` with `_blank` is missing `noopener`
  --> <FIXTURE>/vulnerable_full.vue:27:1
   |
27 | window.open('https://example.com', '_blank')
   | ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ here
   |
   = help: Add `noopener` (or `noreferrer`, which implies `noopener`) to the `windowFeatures` string: `window.open(url, '_blank', 'noopener,width=400')`. Without it the opened tab can call `window.opener.location = ...` and phish the originating page.
error[vue/security/no-fetch-without-timeout]: `fetch` is called without an `AbortSignal`
  --> <FIXTURE>/vulnerable_full.vue:28:1
   |
28 | fetch('/api/users')
   | ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ here
   |
   = help: Pass a `signal` from an `AbortController` so the request can be cancelled: `fetch(url, { signal: ctrl.signal })`. Without it, a slow or unreachable host can hang the call indefinitely, exhausting the connection pool and leaking user state. Pair with a `setTimeout` to bound the wait time.
note[vue/best-practice/no-watch-with-callback]: `watch` with a callback can leak memory if not cleaned up
  --> <FIXTURE>/vulnerable_full.vue:19:1
   |
19 | watch(userInput, (n) => { console.log(n) })
   | ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ here
   |
   = help: Prefer `watchEffect`, or make sure the watcher is stopped via the returned handle inside `onScopeDispose` / `onUnmounted`.
warning[vue/best-practice/v-for-missing-key]: `v-for` is missing a `:key` binding
 --> <FIXTURE>/vulnerable_full.vue:7:5
  |
7 |     <li v-for="item in items">{{ item }}</li>
  |     ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ here
  |
  = help: Without a stable `:key`, Vue falls back to index-based reconciliation which produces wrong DOM updates and loses component state when the list reorders. Add `:key="item.id"` (or any stable identifier).

13 violations: 3 critical, 7 high, 2 medium, 1 low
